 "output": "5"}, {"input": "nums = [123, 246, 369, 492, 615, 738, 861, 984, 1107, 1230, 1353, 1476, 1599, 1722, 1845, 1968, 2091, 2214, 2337, 2460], k = 123", "output": "191"}, {"input": "nums = [999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937,999999937], k = 999999937", "output": "55"}, {"input": "nums = [81, 27, 9, 3, 1, 243, 729], k = 3", "output": "4"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven an integer array nums and an integer k, return the number of subarrays of nums where the greatest common divisor of the subarray's elements is k.\nA subarray is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\nThe greatest common divisor of an array is the largest integer that evenly divides all the array elements.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [9,3,1,2,6,3], k = 3\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: The subarrays of nums where 3 is the greatest common divisor of all the subarray's elements are:\n- [9,3,1,2,6,3]\n- [9,3,1,2,6,3]\n- [9,3,1,2,6,3]\n- [9,3,1,2,6,3]\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [4], k = 7\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There are no subarrays of nums where 7 is the greatest common divisor of all the subarray's elements.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 1000\n1 <= nums[i], k <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def subarrayGCD(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve the problem of finding the number of subarrays where the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the subarray's elements is equal to a given integer \\( k \\), we can use a nested loop approach. The outer loop will iterate over each starting point of the subarray, and the inner loop will iterate over each ending point of the subarray starting from the current starting point. For each subarray, we will calculate the GCD of its elements and check if it matches \\( k \\).\n\nHere's the complete solution:\n\n```python\nfrom math import gcd\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def subarrayGCD(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        count = 0\n        n = len(nums)\n        \n        # Iterate over each starting point of the subarray\n        for i in range(n):\n            current_gcd = nums[i]\n            # Iterate over each ending point of the subarray starting from i\n            for j in range(i, n):\n                current_gcd = gcd(current_gcd, nums[j])\n                # If the GCD of the current subarray is k, increment the count\n                if current_gcd == k:\n                    count += 1\n                # If the GCD becomes less than k, no need to check further\n                elif current_gcd < k:\n                    break\n        \n        return count\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n\n1. **Outer Loop (`for i in range(n)`):** This loop iterates over each possible starting index of the subarray.\n2. **Inner Loop (`for j in range(i, n)`):** This loop iterates over each possible ending index of the subarray starting from the current starting index \\( i \\).\n3. **GCD Calculation (`current_gcd = gcd(current_gcd, nums[j])`):** For each subarray defined by the indices \\( i \\) and \\( j \\), we calculate the GCD of the elements from index \\( i \\) to \\( j \\).\n4. **Count Increment (`if current_gcd == k`):** If the GCD of the current subarray is equal to \\( k \\), we increment the count.\n5. **Break Condition (`elif current_gcd < k`):** If the GCD of the current subarray becomes less than \\( k \\), it will never be equal to \\( k \\) by adding more elements, so we can break out of the inner loop early to optimize the solution.\n\nThis approach ensures that we check all possible subarrays and count those whose GCD is equal to \\( k \\). The time complexity of this solution is \\( O(n^2 \\log(\\text{max\\_value})) \\), where \\( n \\) is the length of the array and \\( \\text{max\\_value} \\) is the maximum value in the array, due to the GCD calculation.", "estimated_date": 1666483200000}